simp_all [h₉₃₅]\n            <;>\n            linarith\n          exact h₉₃₄\n        -- Use the fact that the stopped value is decreasing\n        filter_upwards [ae_restrict_mem (measurableSet_univ : MeasurableSet (Set.univ : Set Ω))] with ω\n        exact h₉₃₃ ω\n      -- Use the fact that the stopped value is decreasing\n      exact h₉₃₂\n    -- Use the fact that the stopped value is decreasing\n    exact le_trans h₉₂ h₉₃\n  exact h₉",
      "\n  have h₁ : (s : ℕ) → 1 / (↑s : ℝ) ^ 2 < 1 := by\n    intro s\n    cases s with\n    | zero => norm_num\n    | succ s =>\n      have h₂ : (1 : ℝ) / (↑(s + 1) : ℝ) ^ 2 < 1 := by\n        have h₃ : (1 : ℝ) / (↑(s + 1) : ℝ) ^ 2 < 1 := by\n          apply (div_lt_one (by positivity)).mpr\n          norm_cast\n          nlinarith\n        exact h₃\n      simpa using h₂\n  \n  exact by sorry",
      "\n   - But submartingale gives `X_τ ≤ E[X_k | hτ]`.\n   - Not sure yet.\n2. However, perhaps we need to use the submartingale condition in the following way: if `s ≤ t`, then `X_s ≤ E[X_t | h_s]`.\n   - And if `h_s ⊆ h_t`, then `E[X_t | h_s] ≤ E[X_t | h_t] = X_t`. \n   - Therefore, `X_s ≤ X_t` if `s ≤ t` and `h_s ⊆ h_t`.\n   - But perhaps not directly useful.\n\nBut after some more thought, perhaps it is better to think this way:\n1. For each `ω`, because `X_{· ω}` is right continuous and `τ(ω) ≤ k`, perhaps `X_{τ(ω)} ≤ sup_{s ≥ τ(",
